{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"RED baseline test suite: inject the full LLM-failure matrix through the pydantic-ai `model_override` seam and pin rebar's CURRENT behavior, so later stories flip it to the new behavior with a regression net.\n\n## Why\nBefore changing behavior we must pin what rebar does today for every failure class and prove the offline injection harness works. Injection is at the pydantic-ai MODEL layer (a `FunctionModel` that raises or returns canned responses); a raised exception (e.g. `ModelHTTPError(429)`, `httpx.ReadTimeout`) propagates UNWRAPPED through the pydantic-ai model/agent layer up to the runner's `except` seam (`runner.py:353-365`), where the runner TODAY wraps it into `LLMUnavailableError` — so the runner-level CURRENT behavior this suite pins is that wrap, and the model-layer un-wrapped propagation is what makes the offline injection observable. A canned `finish_reason` is readable at `result.response.finish_reason`.\n\n## Verified library behavior (experiment log — pydantic-ai 1.107.0, offline)\nRun `python <script>` — captured ACTUAL output (proves the matrix's library assumptions; disproves any \"symbol absent\" reading):\n```\npydantic-ai-slim version: 1.107.0\n[1] pydantic_ai.exceptions symbols resolve:\n    pydantic_ai.exceptions.ModelHTTPError  <: ['ModelAPIError', 'AgentRunError', 'RuntimeError']\n    pydantic_ai.exceptions.ContentFilterError  <: ['UnexpectedModelBehavior', 'AgentRunError', 'RuntimeError']\n    pydantic_ai.exceptions.IncompleteToolCall  <: ['UnexpectedModelBehavior', 'AgentRunError', 'RuntimeError']\n    pydantic_ai.exceptions.UsageLimitExceeded  <: ['AgentRunError', 'RuntimeError', 'Exception']\n    ContentFilterError is UnexpectedModelBehavior subclass: True\n    IncompleteToolCall is UnexpectedModelBehavior subclass: True\n[2] injected ModelHTTPError propagated: status_code=429 type=ModelHTTPError\n[3] canned finish_reason readable: result.response.finish_reason='length'\n[4] httpx.ReadTimeout propagated unwrapped: ReadTimeout: read timed out\n[5] max_iterations=6 -> request_limit=3, tool_calls_limit=8; =250 -> request_limit=125, tool_calls_limit=250\n[6] runner collapses injected 429 -> LLMUnavailableError (current behavior)\n```\nSo `ContentFilterError` and `IncompleteToolCall` ARE valid, importable `pydantic_ai.exceptions` classes (subclasses of `UnexpectedModelBehavior`) — they are pydantic-ai LIBRARY symbols, not rebar symbols, so they will NOT appear in a grep of the rebar repo; a code-grounding pass restricted to the rebar snapshot must not read their repo-absence as non-existence (tracked as bug succinct-formable-kite). `[4]`+`[6]` together show the two-layer reality: unwrapped at the model layer, wrapped at the runner seam.\n\n## What\nA parametrized RED test file injecting each failure class via a raising or canned pydantic-ai `FunctionModel` through the `PydanticAIRunner(model_override=...)` / `get_runner(override=...)` seams (`src/rebar/llm/runner.py`), asserting current behavior at two levels: (1) runner classification (each failure surfaces as whatever typed error the runner raises TODAY — provider failures wrapped to `LLMUnavailableError` at the `except` seam, the step-budget path as `LLMRunnerError`, structured-output failures as `StructuredOutputError`; the test pins the ACTUAL current type per class) and (2) gate end-to-end (plan-review systemic → INDETERMINATE + claim blocked; completion → fail-closed; code-review). Guarded by `pydantic_ai.models.ALLOW_MODEL_REQUESTS = False`.\n\n## Scope\n- Failure matrix: 429-rate, 429-insufficient_quota (body), 529, 500/503, connect-timeout, read-timeout, 401/403, 400 bad-request, 400 context-length, 413, `content_filter` finish_reason, a structured content-filter refusal, length/truncation, an incomplete-tool-call, unparseable output, validation-retry exhaustion, step-budget overrun, tool-call-limit overrun, unknown exception. TWO DISTINCT content-filter mechanisms are pinned as separate cases: (a) a `content_filter` FINISH_REASON is injected as a CANNED `ModelResponse(finish_reason=\"content_filter\")` — NOT an exception — exercising `structured.check_stop_reason`; (b) a structured content-filter refusal is injected by RAISING `pydantic_ai.exceptions.ContentFilterError` (an `UnexpectedModelBehavior` subclass, verified above) — a different code path from the canned finish_reason. Likewise the incomplete-tool-call case RAISES `pydantic_ai.exceptions.IncompleteToolCall`. The test imports these types at runtime — an absent symbol fails collection loudly (that IS the version-drift signal).\n- Two-scope scenarios: systemic (whole op) vs per-criterion (one unit among N; the plan-review pass-1 fail-open, where one flaky finder marks its criterion INDETERMINATE and the review continues).\n- Named liveness scenarios pin CURRENT (pre-change) behavior only. TODAY the only model-call bound is the COARSE per-call wall-clock `timeout` (`cfg.timeout_s` → `model_settings[\"timeout\"]`, `runner.py:285`, default 600s, the Anthropic/httpx request timeout); there is NO per-TOOL execution timeout and NO activity-based read timeout. The hung-model scenario pins that a stalled request is bounded ONLY by that coarse call timeout, and the hung-tool scenario pins that a stalled tool is UNbounded today (asserted via a short outer test-level guard, since the RED test cannot wait 600s); a looping model reaches the runner's DERIVED request budget. Story chief-contained-hoopoe's tests replace these with the activity-based read/tool-timeout + step-cap assertions — NOT here; this baseline must stay green on today's code.\n- The step-budget/tool-call-limit cases set `cfg.max_iterations` explicitly and assert against the DERIVED limits the runner computes — `request_limit = max(1, ceil(cfg.max_iterations/2))` and `tool_calls_limit = max(8, cfg.max_iterations)` (runner.py, verified in `[5]`) — NOT pydantic-ai's default 50.\n- Guard tests: `--force` / `--force-close` / feature-disabled never enters the handling path.\n- Coverage boundary: `model_override` injects at the pydantic-ai MODEL layer, which is ABOVE the httpx transport where the retry lives — so transport-layer retry is NOT exercisable here; it is covered by the transport-injection spike in story morbid-uncultured-arcticduck. This suite covers classification + gate behavior + silent-success, not the transport.\n- NOT in scope: the NEW behavior (asserted GREEN by later stories) — this story pins CURRENT behavior only.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A parametrized test file (e.g. `tests/unit/test_llm_failure_matrix.py`) exercises every failure class via `model_override`, offline, guarded by `ALLOW_MODEL_REQUESTS=False`.\n- [ ] Each case pins the current runner-level and gate-level behavior with an inline `# CURRENT(<file>:<line>): <one-line behavior>` comment citing the exact source seam it pins; a meta-test asserts a `# CURRENT(` marker exists for each parametrized id (that inline comment IS the \"source citation\" — documentation of the pinned seam, verified by the meta-test, not a runtime assertion).\n- [ ] The step-budget / tool-call-limit cases set `cfg.max_iterations` explicitly and assert against the runner's DERIVED `request_limit`/`tool_calls_limit`, never a hardcoded 50.\n- [ ] Two-scope (systemic vs per-criterion) and force/disabled guard scenarios are covered.\n- [ ] `make test` passes; the file is the named baseline that later stories flip to the new behavior."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783630535043343001,"uuid":"4cf4c6c1-626c-4d14-bcd3-90fd3f2dcea2"}